    <h1 id="title">The Origin Of Cake</h1>
    <p id="h1-p">Cakes history is both long and fascinatig</p>
    <div id="img-div">
      <img id="image" src="https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2016/02/29/00/19/cake-1227842_1280.jpg" alt="a piece of chocolate cake with filling"/>
      <figcaption id="img-caption">Who doesn't love cake?</figcaption>
    </div>
    <section id="tribute-info">
      <h2>Here's a time line of cakes origin</h2>
     <ul class="cake-origin-list">
  <li class="cake-origin-item ancient-egypt">
    <strong>Ancient Egypt:</strong>
    <ul class="cake-origin-sublist">
      <li>Early forms of cake were more like bread, sweetened with honey and flavored with nuts or dried fruits.</li>
      <li>Often used in religious rituals and offerings.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li class="cake-origin-item ancient-greece">
    <strong>Ancient Greece:</strong>
    <ul class="cake-origin-sublist">
      <li>Made cheesecakes using simple ingredients like flour, honey, and cheese.</li>
      <li>Cakes were sometimes shaped like the moon and offered to Artemis, the moon goddess.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li class="cake-origin-item ancient-rome">
    <strong>Ancient Rome:</strong>
    <ul class="cake-origin-sublist">
      <li>Developed more complex cakes using eggs and butter.</li>
      <li>Often made small honey cakes to celebrate special occasions.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li class="cake-origin-item middle-ages">
    <strong>Middle Ages (Europe):</strong>
    <ul class="cake-origin-sublist">
      <li>Cakes were dense and bread-like, sweetened with dried fruits and spices.</li>
      <li>Reserved for celebrations due to the high cost of ingredients.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li class="cake-origin-item seventeenth-century">
    <strong>17th Century (Europe):</strong>
    <ul class="cake-origin-sublist">
      <li>Introduction of round cake molds and icing.</li>
      <li>Sugar became more widely available due to colonial trade.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li class="cake-origin-item eighteenth-century">
    <strong>18th Century (Industrial Revolution):</strong>
    <ul class="cake-origin-sublist">
      <li>Development of refined flour and baking powder made lighter cakes possible.</li>
      <li>Cakes became more accessible to the middle class.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li class="cake-origin-item nineteenth-century">
    <strong>19th Century:</strong>
    <ul class="cake-origin-sublist">
      <li>The layered and frosted cake as we know it today emerged.</li>
      <li>Victorian-era cakes became centerpiece desserts for special occasions.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li class="cake-origin-item twentieth-century-present">
    <strong>20th Century to Present:</strong>
    <ul class="cake-origin-sublist">
      <li>Cakes became a staple for birthdays, weddings, and holidays.</li>
      <li>Mass production and cake mixes made baking easy and popular worldwide.</li>
      <li>Global influences led to a wide variety of cake styles and flavors.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

      
